          Every year, Malaysian businesses waste thousands of ringgit on packaging — not because they buy expensive boxes, but because they buy the <em>wrong size</em>. A box that's too big wastes filler material and increases shipping cost. A box that's too small gets stuffed, bends, and damages your product. Getting the size right is one of the simplest ways to cut costs and improve your customer's unboxing experience.
        </p>

        <p>This guide walks you through everything you need to know — from understanding box measurements to matching sizes to your products.</p>

        ---

        <h2>Understanding Box Dimensions: L × W × H</h2>

        <p>All carton boxes are measured in three dimensions, always in this order:</p>

        <div class="article-callout article-callout--yellow">
          <strong>Length (L) × Width (W) × Height (H)</strong><br />
          These are the <em>internal</em> dimensions — the usable space inside the box. Always measure your product and match it to the internal size.
        </div>

        <p>For example, a box listed as <strong>40 × 30 × 25 cm</strong> has 40 cm of internal length, 30 cm of internal width, and 25 cm of internal depth. The external dimensions will be slightly larger due to the cardboard thickness — typically 1–2 cm per side.</p>

        <p><strong>Key rule:</strong> Always size your box to the product's dimensions, not the other way around. Your product should fit with <strong>3–5 cm of clearance</strong> on each side for protective padding.</p>

        ---

        <h2>The 4 Standard Sizes We Carry — and What They're For</h2>

        <p>At Quinocycle, we stock four standard sizes in both new and used carton boxes. Here's a practical breakdown of which size suits which products:</p>

