        ---

        <h2>Single Wall vs Double Wall: Which Do You Need?</h2>

        <p>This is a question we get a lot. Here's the simple answer:</p>

        <div class="article-two-col">
          <div class="article-panel article-panel--light">
            <h3>Single Wall</h3>
            <p>One layer of corrugated fluting between two flat sheets. Lighter, cheaper, and sufficient for most e-commerce parcels under 10 kg.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>✓ Best for retail, online sellers</li>
              <li>✓ Lighter shipping weight</li>
              <li>✓ Lower cost per box</li>
              <li>✗ Not ideal for heavy or fragile items</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="article-panel article-panel--dark">
            <h3>Double Wall</h3>
            <p>Two layers of fluting for extra strength and cushioning. Recommended for anything heavy, fragile, or being moved long distances.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>✓ Best for movers, logistics</li>
              <li>✓ Handles heavier loads (10–30 kg)</li>
              <li>✓ Better stacking strength</li>
              <li>✗ Slightly heavier and costs more</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        ---

        <h2>Practical Sizing Guide by Business Type</h2>

        <h3>For Online Sellers (Shopee, Lazada, TikTok Shop)</h3>
        <p>Your main concern is keeping shipping costs low and ensuring your product arrives safely. Courier companies like J&T and Poslaju charge by volumetric weight, so oversized boxes directly increase your shipping cost.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>For items under 500g: Size <strong>S</strong> is usually sufficient</li>
          <li>For fashion, shoes, accessories: Size <strong>M</strong> works for most SKUs</li>
          <li>For bundle deals or multi-item orders: Size <strong>L</strong></li>
          <li>Avoid boxes that are more than 5 cm larger than your product on any side</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="article-callout">
          <strong>💡 Pro tip:</strong> Standardise on 2–3 box sizes. Fewer SKUs means you can buy in higher volume, which reduces your per-box cost significantly when ordering wholesale.
        </div>

        <h3>For Retail Businesses (Physical Stores)</h3>
        <p>Retail packaging serves double duty — protection during delivery and presentation in-store. For products displayed in boxes, the outer dimension matters too.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Match box size to product tightly — minimal filler looks more premium</li>
          <li>Single wall is fine for most retail products</li>
          <li>If you sell fragile items (ceramics, glass), go one size up and add padding</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>For Mover Companies</h3>
        <p>Moving boxes need to be versatile and strong. Customers pack everything from clothes to books to kitchenware — sometimes all in the same box.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Keep a mix of <strong>M, L, and XL</strong> sizes on hand</li>
          <li>Always use double wall for L and XL boxes — they'll be stacked and loaded</li>
          <li>Used boxes are a cost-effective choice for moving — they're strong enough for one-time use and significantly cheaper</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>For Logistics &amp; Warehousing</h3>
        <p>Consistency is key. Standardised box sizes make stacking, labelling, and palletising far more efficient.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Work with your operations team to define 3–5 standard sizes</li>
          <li>Order in bulk to reduce unit cost and simplify reordering</li>
          <li>Double wall for anything going into cold storage or heavy-load racking</li>
        </ul>

        ---

        <h2>The Quick Sizing Checklist</h2>

        <p>Before placing your next order, run through this checklist:</p>

        <div class="article-checklist">
          <div class="checklist-item">
            <span class="checklist-num">1</span>
            <div>
              <strong>Measure your product</strong>
              <p>Length × Width × Height. Round up to the nearest centimetre.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="checklist-item">
            <span class="checklist-num">2</span>
            <div>
              <strong>Add clearance</strong>
              <p>Add 3–5 cm on each dimension for padding material (bubble wrap, paper, etc.).</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="checklist-item">
            <span class="checklist-num">3</span>
            <div>
              <strong>Check the weight</strong>
              <p>If your packed box will exceed 10 kg, choose double wall.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="checklist-item">
            <span class="checklist-num">4</span>
            <div>
              <strong>Consider fragility</strong>
              <p>Fragile or irregular items need more clearance and stronger walls.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="checklist-item">
            <span class="checklist-num">5</span>
            <div>
              <strong>Standardise where possible</strong>
              <p>Fewer sizes = higher volume per SKU = lower cost per box.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        ---

        <h2>New vs Used — Does It Matter for Sizing?</h2>

        <p>Used boxes are a great cost-saving option, especially for movers, storage, or internal logistics. One thing to note: used boxes come in <em>assorted dimensions</em> within a size range (e.g., "Large" used boxes are approximately 60 × 40 × 40 cm, but may vary slightly by ±5 cm).</p>

        <p>If you need exact, consistent dimensions — for example, fitting into specific packaging lines or branded unboxing — go with <strong>new boxes</strong>. If you need strong, functional boxes for general use and want to save up to 50% on cost, <strong>used boxes</strong> are excellent value.</p>

